Time Series Analysis¶

Please import the student engagement data engagement_data.xlsx. In this dataset we know students' page visits on different days and times. Students are labeled by their achievement levels.

In [ ]:
df = pd.read_excel('engagement-data.xlsx', index_col=0, parse_dates=True)
df.head(5)

Our data contains students visits on specific hours of each day. To start with we should compute students' daily page visit counts (i.e., how many pages a student visited per each day in the dataset).

To achieve, we should first apply groupby with student_id and achievement_level. Grouping by student_id is necessary because we want to compute total interactions per student. achievement_level is also included in the grouping just to carry over this information as index value. If not, achievement_level column would be lost totally. We will need it later

On the grouped data you should apply resample by day (D) and then the the size function to count the number of interactions.

The final outcome should be stored in daily_interactions, which should look like the following:

In [ ]:
daily_interactions = df.groupby(['achievement_level', 'student_id']).resample('D').size()

We are interested in knowing students' average page visits for a period of 7 days throughout the semester. We will apply a moving average (i.e., rolling) and store the result in rolling_mean.

rolling_mean will be a Series. You should apply to_frame(name='avg_engagement') to convert it into a dataframe.

In [ ]:
rolling_mean = daily_interactions.rolling(window=7, center=True).mean()
rolling_mean = rolling_mean.to_frame(name='avg_engagement')
rolling_mean

Now, our data is ready. Please execute the following code to visualize the rolling_mean. This visualization will display all students' daily interaction with 7-day rolling mean:

In [ ]:
sns.scatterplot(data=rolling_mean, x='timestamp', y='avg_engagement', hue='student_id', legend=False, size = 1)
plt.title('7-Day Rolling Mean of Daily Interactions')
plt.ylabel('Mean Daily Interactions')
plt.xlabel('Date')

plt.show()

I think it looks very messy since we have all students' data at once. Since we set hue='student_id', different colors were assigned to each student. Although this helps us differentiate between students, it is still almost impossible to make sense of it.

One option could be to color students by their achievement levels. So, let's change the visualization by setting hue to achievement_level. hue helps us to group data by assigning a varying colors to each group:

In [ ]:
sns.scatterplot(data=rolling_mean, x='timestamp', y='avg_engagement',
                hue='achievement_level', legend=True, size = 1)
plt.title('7-Day Rolling Mean of Daily Interactions')
plt.ylabel('Mean Daily Interactions')
plt.xlabel('Date')

plt.show()

Now, the visualization is a bit more interpretable. High achievers (blue points) are mostly located at the top section and therefore they engaged quite with the tutorial pages. Mid achievers (green points) are mostly located just below them. The low achievers (orange dots) are usually at the bottom part.

But, since we still have a mean score for each student, the graph is still not very clear.

What if we create a mean score per each achievement group? With this approach, we could obtain a simpler graph like this:

To start with tihs task, in the below cell, you should group rolling_mean by 'achievement_level', 'timestamp'. We do this because we are interested in each achievement groups' average engagement not each students' specific engagement.

After groupby, you should select avg_engagement column and compute mean. So, basically we are computing the average engagement of each achievement level at teach timestamp.

Store the final result to rolling_mean2 and print it. Your output should match the following:

In [ ]:
rolling_mean2 = rolling_mean.groupby(['achievement_level', 'timestamp'])['avg_engagement'].mean()
rolling_mean2 = rolling_mean2.to_frame(name='avg_engagement')
rolling_mean2
